Business Requirements Document (BRD) – EDD Case Management System (English)
Scope: Enhanced Due Diligence (EDD) only – excluding Volooras Risk Classification Engine. The system monitors and manages high‑risk clients based on T24 data and QCB KYC API input. It tracks EDD triggers, assigns cases, manages workflows, and ensures compliance with Qatar Islamic Bank (QIB) policies and central bank requirements.
1. Purpose
This document defines the requirements for a dedicated EDD Case Management System. The system supports the controlled execution, tracking, and governance of EDD activities. It covers client segmentation, case creation, risk monitoring, SLA management, dashboard reporting, and integration with T24 and QCB KYC API. The solution is aligned with QIB governance and regulatory expectations.
2. Scope Definition
In Scope
•	Management of EDD cases only (no CDD risk classification).
•	Integration with T24 for retrieving client segment, KYC dates, and risk triggers.
•	Integration with QCB KYC API (subject to user consent) for retrieving mandatory documents and verifying client details.
•	Case creation and routing to business units (Mass, Tamayuz, Private Banking) based on T24 segment.
•	SLA monitoring for both business review and EDD operations.
•	Audit trail and full lifecycle reporting.
•	Ability to fetch and present supporting documents (e.g. salary certificates, passport, ID) from DMS for business review.
•	Notifications and approval workflows including Maker–Checker at business and CDD levels.
Out of Scope
•	Risk scoring or classification (handled by upstream systems).
•	Modifying customer risk rating in T24.
•	AML transaction monitoring logic.
3. Core Principles
•	EDD is initiated after a customer is classified as high risk by the upstream risk classification engine (T24/CRP).
•	Business units review cases and provide recommendations, but cannot reject cases; they can suggest actions such as restricting the account.
•	CDD performs EDD processing and approvals. Maker–Checker principle applies at each stage.
•	Clear separation of responsibilities among business, EDD operations, and compliance.
•	Audit readiness and full traceability of each action.
•	Integration with QCB KYC API to retrieve mandatory KYC documents when customer consent is available.
•	Notifications to clients via pop‑up and SMS when additional documents or clarifications are required, with dynamic text templates managed by marketing.
4. Upstream Risk Classification Sources
Source	Description
T24 / CRP	Official customer risk classification (High / Medium / Low)
QCB KYC API	External regulatory data (subject to consent)
Management Referral	Exceptional cases referred by management or compliance
5. EDD Trigger Reasons
High-risk classification is determined by fields from T24 and risk indicators. Triggers include:
•	Politically Exposed Person (PEP) flag
•	High-risk occupation
•	High-risk nationality or residency
•	Non-resident status
•	Private Banking segment
•	Source of wealth / funds sensitivity
•	Unusual or complex transaction profile
•	Cash-intensive activity
•	Exposure to sanctioned countries
•	Large or sensitive initial deposit
•	Guardian / Power of Attorney / POA
•	Multiple banking relationships
•	Management or Compliance referral
6. Business Segmentation and Routing
Customer segment is retrieved from T24 and determines the case routing:
Customer Segment	Business Department
Mass	Mass Banking
Tamayuz	Tamayuz Banking
Private Banking	Private Banking
Each business department has a designated supervisor who can assign cases to specific Relationship Managers (RMs) based on RIM number or employee ID. Cases can be transferred between segments (e.g. from Mass to Tamayuz) if necessary.
7. Workflow & SLAs
1.	Case Creation: When a customer is classified as high risk, the system automatically opens an EDD case in Flow. The case ID, creation timestamp, segment, and reason code are recorded.
2.	Business Department Stage: Business units review the case, verify the information, retrieve supporting documents from DMS (passport, ID, salary certificate), and provide comments. They cannot reject cases; instead, they can recommend account restrictions or temporary freezes with justification. The case is then submitted to EDD operations.
3.	EDD Operations Stage (CDD): EDD operations perform enhanced due diligence, request additional documents via QCB KYC API, review supporting documents, and determine whether to approve or maintain restrictions. Maker–Checker approvals apply.
4.	Notification: If additional documents are required or if there is data mismatch between T24 and QCB API, the system generates a pop‑up on the client’s mobile banking app and sends an SMS with a reference number, requesting the client to upload the required documents via the mobile app or submit them at any branch. Dynamic templates managed by marketing department ensure proper messaging.
5.	Case Closure: Upon EDD completion, updated data is sent back to T24. Fields not originally present in T24 must be created in a new “EDD” section of the client profile. The system records completion date, decision (approved or escalated), next EDD review date, and audit trail.
Business SLAs
Department	SLA Duration (from case creation to submission to CDD)
Mass Banking	As per bank policy
Tamayuz Banking	As per bank policy
Private Banking	As per bank policy
EDD Operations SLA
The operations SLA applies from receipt of the case until EDD is completed. Each stage is monitored separately.
8. Dashboards & Reporting
•	Business Dashboard: Shows case volumes, pending cases, SLA performance, and aging analysis per segment.
•	EDD Operations Dashboard: Shows cases received from business, current status, closure outcomes, and escalations.
•	Management Dashboard: Provides overall EDD visibility, SLA compliance, volumes by segment, and trend analysis.
9. Key Dates and Integration
•	EDD Case Creation Date and Completion Date: Generated by the system.
•	Last KYC Date: Pulled from T24.
•	Next EDD Due Date: Calculated based on review cycle and last KYC date.
•	Consent Status: If consent is available, the system retrieves documents from QCB KYC API.
10. Periodic EDD Reviews
Periodic reviews are generated based on the Next EDD Due Date. Each review opens a new linked case, ensuring continuous compliance.
11. Roles & Responsibilities
Role	Responsibilities
Business	Review and prepare case; cannot reject; provide comments and recommendations; Maker–Checker approval within business
EDD Operations (CDD)	Perform enhanced due diligence, review documents, and close or restrict the account; Maker–Checker applies
Compliance	Review escalated cases and ensure regulatory adherence
Management	Provide oversight and ensure governance
Audit	Read-only access for auditing purposes
12. Audit & Governance
•	Full audit trail of every action
•	Timestamped events and statuses
•	SLA compliance monitoring and reporting
•	Historical traceability of all cases
13. Conclusion
The EDD Case Management System will provide an automated, transparent, and governed process for handling high-risk customers. It integrates with T24 and QCB KYC API to retrieve and update critical data, includes dynamic notifications, and ensures compliance with QIB and regulatory requirements.
